name: 3-trifluoromethylaniline
Reason: The basic unit, benzene, has a melting point of 5.5°C. The trifluoromethyl group is an electron-withdrawing group due to the strong electronegativity of fluorine atoms and slightly lowers the melting point because it weakens the π-π stacking interactions between benzene rings, causing less effective packing (-5). The amino group is a mild electron-donating group and tends to form hydrogen bonds, which increases the melting point (+10). The effects of the two functional groups partially counteract each other.
